ce:section.ce:para:
The G-CDs concentrations used in this study were selected based on the range commonly investigated in previous droplet-scale combustion experiments (see 
                           Table S2
                        ). Typically, nanoparticle concentrations in reported studies ranged from 0.001% to 5.00% w/w, as noted in the literature [2–4,13,14,17,20,57,58]. By selecting concentrations within this range, the study facilitates meaningful comparisons with previous research and helps to contextualize the findings in relation to existing studies.

Fig. 11 d and 11e compare the global combustion rate (
K
Global
) of Jet-A-based nanofuels at stages 3 and 4, respectively. In the weak puffing stage (stage 3), the combustion rate trend closely mirrors that of stage 2. The highest increase in combustion rate, 20.45%, was observed at 0.10% w/w, likely due to the additional contributions from puffing. Beyond 0.10% w/w and up to 0.50% w/w, no plateau in the combustion rate was observed, but the increase at 0.50% w/w was only 1.09% higher than the base fuel. This suggests that the benefits of thermal transport enhancement and puffing were largely offset by significant particle accumulation and aggregation near the droplet surface. At higher concentrations, up to 1.00% w/w, the combustion rate continued to decline, resulting in a 7.74% reduction compared to the base fuel due to these aggregation effects. In contrast, during the strong puffing stage (stage 4), the combustion rate followed a different trend. Intense puffing became the primary mechanism for transporting fuel mass to the flame zone, driven by the multicomponent nature of the base fuel. A consistent improvement in combustion rate was observed for all nanofuel concentrations compared to the base fuel, with increases ranging from 6.00% to 27.00% for concentrations between 0.01% and 0.50% w/w, and an increase of approximately 11.00% at 1.00% w/w. The increase in particle concentration contributed to pressure buildup, resulting in more intense puffing and the ejection of vapor or secondary droplets, which improved fuel mass transport to the flame zone. The highest combustion rate increase, 27.09%, was observed at 0.50% w/w. Beyond this concentration, although the combustion rate remained higher than that of the base fuel, it slightly declined due to increased particle accumulation and aggregation. A quantitative analysis of puffing characteristics, such as puffing intensity and occurrences, provides further insights into the differences in combustion rates between stages 3 and 4. As detailed in S1.4: Puffing Intensity Quantification, puffing intensity measures the cumulative capacity of the droplet to fragment into smaller parts, while puffing occurrences quantify the frequency of these events [15,74,75]. Fig. 12 compares puffing intensity and occurrences in stages 3 and 4, as well as throughout the entire ROI period (referred to as “Global”). The analysis revealed that puffing intensity in stage 3 was significantly lower (
PI < 0.20
) than stage 4 (
PI : 0.35 ∼
4.00
), reinforcing its classification as the weak puffing stage. Additionally, fewer puffing occurrences were observed in stage 3 compared to stage 4. These combined effects in stage 4 led to more efficient fuel mass transport via secondary droplet ejection, which contributed to a higher combustion rate at all particle concentrations compared to base fuel.
